nson was also fifth highest among running backs in the [[vertical jump]] with a 35-inch jump. His 10-foot, 10-inch broad jump was third best among the running backs.<ref>[http://www.nfl.com/combine/top-performers?tabIndex=0 Top Performers]. Nfl.com. Retrieved on June 2, 2012.</ref>\n\n{{nfl predraft\n|    height ft = 5\n|    height in = 11\n|       weight = 197\n|         dash = 4.24\n|   ten split  = 1.40\n| twenty split = 2.41\n|      shuttle = \n|   cone drill = \n|     vertical = 35\n|     broad ft = 10\n|     broad in = 10\n|        bench = \n|    wonderlic = 10/21\n|     arm span = {{frac|30|1|4}}\n|    hand span = {{frac|7|1|4}}\n|         note = All values from [[NFL Combine]];<ref>[http://www.nfldraftscout.com/ratings/dsprofile.php?pyid=32966&draftyear=2008&genpos=RB Chris Johnson, East Carolina, RB : 2008 NFL Draft Scout Player Profile]. Nfldraftscout.com (September 21, 2006). Retrieved on 2012-06-02.</ref>  Wonderlic test taken twice<ref>[http://www.nfl.com/combine/profiles/chris-johnson?id=262#tabs:tab-analysis NFL Combine Participants]. Nfl.com. Retrieved on June 2, 2012.</ref>\n}}\n\n===Tennessee Titans===\nJohnson was drafted by the [[Tennessee Titans]] in the first round (24th overall) of the [[2008 NFL Draft]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/years/2008/draft.htm |title=2008 NFL Draft Listing |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=March 17, 2018}}</ref> He was the highest [[East Carolina]] player selected in the NFL Draft since linebacker [[Robert Jones (American football)|Robert Jones]] went 24th overall in the [[1992 NFL Draft]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/schools/eastcarolina/drafted.htm |title=East Carolina Drafted Players/Alumni |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=March 17, 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn July 26, he signed a five-year, $12 million contract with $7 million guaranteed.<ref>{{cite news |title=Titans, Chris Johnson agree to terms |url=http://www.sportingnews.com/nfl/article/2008-07-26/titans-chris-johnson-agree-terms |work=Sporting News |publisher=sportingnews.com |date=July 26, 2008 |access-date=June 20, 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100620114707/http://www.sportingnews.com/nfl/article/2008-07-26/titans-chris-johnson-agree-terms |archive-date=June 20, 2010 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n====2008 season: Rookie year====\n{{See also|2008 Tennessee Titans season}}\n\nJohnson had his professional debut with the Titans on September 7, 2008 where he played in the season opener against the Jacksonville Jaguars, which the Titans won 17\u201310. Johnson rushed for 93 yards on 15 carries and had 3 receptions for 34 yards and a touchdown.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/200809070oti.htm |title=Jacksonville Jaguars at Tennessee Titans - September 7th, 2008 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=March 17, 2018}}</ref> In only his second career game, Johnson ran for 109 yards on 19 carries, including a 51-yard run, and 2 receptions for 12 yards against the Cincinnati Bengals.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/200809140cin.htm |title=Tennessee Titans at Cincinnati Bengals - September 14th, 2008 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=March 17, 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn September 28, Johnson rushed for the first touchdown of his career against the Minnesota Vikings. Johnson finished the game with 75 all-purpose yards (61 rushing, 14 receiving) and 2 touchdowns.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/200809280oti.htm |title=Minnesota Vikings at Tennessee Titans - September 28th, 2008 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=March 17, 2018}}</ref> In only his sixth professional game, he rushed for 168 yards and a touchdown on only 18 carries against the Kansas City Chiefs on October 19, 2008.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/200810190kan.htm |title=Tennessee Titans at Kansas City Chiefs - October 19th, 2008 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=March 17, 2018}}</ref> Johnson finished the season with 1,228 yards on 251 carries for a 4.9 ypc and 43 receptions for 260 yards and 10 total touchdowns in 15 games. He led all rookies in rushing yards per game with 81.9 ypg.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/J/JohnCh04/gamelog/2008/ |title=Chris Johnson 2008 Game Log |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=March 17, 2018}}</ref>\n\nJohnson finished second in AP Rookie of the Year voting to [[Matt Ryan (American football)|Matt Ryan]] and was elected to the [[2009 Pro Bowl]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/years/2008/probowl.htm |title=2008 NFL Pro Bowlers |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=March 17, 2018}}</ref>\n\nJohnson split carries with running back [[LenDale White]] for the duration of the 2008 season.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/teams/oti/2008.htm |title=2008 Tennessee Titans Statistics & Players |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=March 17, 2018}}</ref> White finished the 2008 season with 773 yards on 200 carries for a 3.9 ypc and 15 rushing touchdowns. They nicknamed this RB tandem \"[[Smash and Dash (disambiguation)|Smash and Dash]].\" Smash referred to White due to his power, and Dash referred to Johnson due to his unusual quickness and speed. Entering into the 2009 season, however, Johnson dismissed the nickname of \"Smash and Dash\" and named himself \"Every Coach's Dream.\"\n[[File:ChrisJohnson28.jpg|thumb|left|200px|Johnson at Titans 2009 Training Camp.]]\n\n====2009 season: Breakout season====\n{{See also|2009 Tennessee Titans season}}\n\nSome consider Johnson's 2009 season to be one of the best ever in NFL history for a running back.<ref>[https://sports.yahoo.com/nfl/blog/shutdown_corner/post/Chris-Johnson-s-2009-Best-ever-season-by-a-runn?urn=nfl-211551 Chris Johnson's 2009: Best ever season by a running back? \u2013 Shutdown Corner \u2013 NFL Blog \u2013 Yahoo! Sports]. Sports.yahoo.com (February 5, 2012). Retrieved on 2012-06-02.</ref> He started the season off with 57 rushing yards in a 13\u201310 loss to the Pittsburgh Steelers.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/200909100pit.htm |title=Tennessee Titans at Pittsburgh Steelers - September 10th, 2009 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=March 17, 2018}}</ref> In the next game, a 34\u201331 loss to the Houston Texans, he had 16 carries for 197 rushing yards and two rushing touchdowns to go along with nine receptions for 87 yards and a receiving touchdown.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/200909200oti.htm |title=Houston Texans at Tennessee Titans - September 20th, 2009 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=March 17, 2018}}</ref> Over the next three games, losses to the New York Jets, Jacksonville Jaguars, and the Indianapolis Colts, he combined for 214 rushing yards.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/200909270nyj.htm |title=Tennessee Titans at New York Jets - September 27th, 2009 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=March 17, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/200910040jax.htm |title=Tennessee Titans at Jacksonville Jaguars - October 4th, 2009 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=March 17, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/200910110oti.htm |title=Indianapolis Colts at Tennessee Titans - October 11th, 2009 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=March 17, 2018}}</ref> In the next game, a 59\u20130 loss to the New England Patriots, he had 128 rushing yards.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/200910180nwe.htm |title=Tennessee Titans at New England Patriots - October 18th, 2009 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=March 17, 2018}}</ref> In the next game, a 30\u201313 victory over the Jacksonville Jaguars, he had 24 carries for 228 rushing yards and two rushing touchdowns.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/200911010oti.htm |title=Jacksonville Jaguars at Tennessee Titans - November 1st, 2009 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=March 17, 2018}}</ref> He followed that up with 135 rushing yards and two rushing touchdowns against the San Francisco 49ers.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/200911080sfo.htm |title=Tennessee Titans at San Francisco 49ers - November 8th, 2009 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=March 17, 2018}}</ref> The next week, against the Buffalo Bills, he had 132 rushing yards and his third consecutive game with two rushing touchdowns to go along with nine receptions for 100 yards.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/200911150oti.htm |title=Buffalo Bills at Tennessee Titans - November 15th, 2009 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=March 17, 2018}}</ref> In the next game, against the Houston Texans, he was held out of the endzone but had 151 rushing yards on 29 carries.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/200911230htx.htm |title=Tennessee Titans at Houston Texans - November 23rd, 2009 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=March 17, 2018}}</ref> He followed that up with 154 rushing yards and a rushing touchdown in the 20\u201317 victory over the Arizona Cardinals.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/200911290oti.htm |title=Arizona Cardinals at Tennessee Titans - November 29th, 2009 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=March 17, 2018}}</ref> On December 13, against the St. Louis Rams, he had 117 rushing yards and two rushing touchdowns to go along with three receptions for 69 yards and a receiving touchdown in the 47\u20137 victory.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/200912130oti.htm |title=St. Louis Rams at Tennessee Titans - December 13th, 2009 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=March 17, 2018}}</ref> In Week 16, on Christmas Day, he had 142 rushing yards and a touchdown in a loss to the San Diego Chargers.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/200912250oti.htm |title=San Diego Chargers at Tennessee Titans - December 25th, 2009 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=March 17, 2018}}</ref> In the regular season finale against the Seattle Seahawks, he had 36 carries for 134 yards and two touchdowns in the 17\u201313 victory.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201001030sea.htm |title=Tennessee Titans at Seattle Seahawks - January 3rd, 2010 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=March 17, 2018}}</ref> Overall, he rushed for 2,006 yards and finished the year with 11 consecutive games with at least 100 rushing yards.<ref>[http://espn.go.com/nfl/player/stats/_/id/11258/chris-johnson Chris Johnson Stats \u2013 Tennessee Titans \u2013 ESPN]. Espn.go.com. Retrieved on June 2, 2012</ref> to become one of only seven players in NFL history to be in the [[2,000-yard club|2,000 rushing yards club]]. He averaged 5.6 yards per carry and 125.4 yards per game to lead the league.<ref>[https://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/J/JohnCh04.htm Chris Johnson NFL & AFL Football Statistics]. Pro-Football-Reference.com (September 23, 1985). Retrieved on 2012-06-02.</ref> He had 2,509 total [[yards from scrimmage]], breaking [[Marshall Faulk]]'s single-season record. He was named the NFL's Offensive Player of the Year in 2009.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/awards/ap-offensive-player-of-the-year.htm |title=AP Offensive Player of the Year Winners |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=March 17, 2018}}</ref> After his 2009 season, he was named to his second Pro Bowl and the media referred to him as \"CJ2K\".<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/years/2009/probowl.htm |title=2009 NFL Pro Bowlers |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=March 17, 2018}}</ref>\n\n====2010 season: Third Pro Bowl season====\n{{See also|2010 Tennessee Titans season}}\n\nTo start the 2010 NFL season, the [[Tennessee Titans]] took on the [[Oakland Raiders]] at [[LP Field]]. Johnson scored on a 76-yard touchdown run in the second quarter and again on a 4-yard run in the third. Johnson had a slow start to the game but finished with 142 yards on 27 carries with a yard per carry average of 5.3 yards to bring his streak of 100-yard rushing games to 12.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201009120oti.htm |title=Oakland Raiders at Tennessee Titans - September 12th, 2010 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=March 17, 2018}}</ref>\n[[File:Antonio Dixon.JPG|thumb|right|200px|Johnson running against the [[Philadelphia Eagles]] in 2010.]]\nThe next week, the Titans took on the [[Pittsburgh Steelers]]. The Steelers ended Johnson's streak of 100 yard games and limited him to only 34 yards. He did have an 85-yard touchdown run but it was called back on a holding penalty.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201009190oti.htm |title=Pittsburgh Steelers at Tennessee Titans - September 19th, 2010 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=March 17, 2018}}</ref>\nThe Titans then took on the [[New York Giants]]. Johnson had 125 yards on 32 carries.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201009260nyg.htm |title=Tennessee Titans at New York Giants - September 26th, 2010 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=March 17, 2018}}</ref> He would next have yet another 100 yard game against the [[Dallas Cowboys]] gaining 131 yards on 19 carries along with two touchdowns one of which ended up being the game winner with 3:28 left.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201010100dal.htm |title=Tennessee Titans at Dallas Cowboys - October 10th, 2010 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=March 17, 2018}}</ref> In the next game, against the Jacksonville Jaguars, he had 111 rushing yards and a rushing touchdown.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201010180jax.htm |title=Tennessee Titans at Jacksonville Jaguars - October 18th, 2010 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=March 17, 2018}}</ref> On November 14, against the Miami Dolphins, he had 117 rushing yard and a rushing touchdown.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201011140mia.htm |title=Tennessee Titans at Miami Dolphins - November 14th, 2010 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=March 17, 2018}}</ref> In the next game, a 19\u201316 loss to the Washington Redskins, he had 130 rushing yards.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201011210oti.htm |title=Washington Redskins at Tennessee Titans - November 21st, 2010 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=March 17, 2018}}</ref> After dreadful performances against the [[Houston Texans]] and [[Jacksonville Jaguars]], Johnson bounced back to rush for 110 yard and 1 touchdown against the Colts.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201011280htx.htm |title=Tennessee Titans at Houston Texans - November 28th, 2010 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=March 17, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201012050oti.htm |title=Jacksonville Jaguars at Tennessee Titans - December 5th, 2010 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=March 17, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201012090oti.htm |title=Indianapolis Colts at Tennessee Titans - December 9th, 2010 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=March 17, 2018}}</ref> In Week 15, in the second game against the Houston Texans, he had 130 rushing yards and a rushing touchdown in the 31\u201317 victory.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201012190oti.htm |title=Houston Texans at Tennessee Titans - December 19th, 2010 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=March 17, 2018}}</ref> Overall, he finished the 2010 season with 1,364 rushing yards and 11 rushing touchdowns.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/J/JohnCh04/gamelog/2010/ |title=Chris Johnson 2010 Game Log |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=March 17, 2018}}</ref> On January 14, 2011, Johnson was selected to the [[2011 Pro Bowl]], his third in three years.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/years/2010/probowl.htm |title=2010 NFL Pro Bowlers |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=March 17, 2018}}</ref>\n\n====2011 season====\n{{See also|2011 Tennessee Titans season}}\n\nDuring the summer training camp prior to the 2011 season, Johnson initially did not show up to camp, pending contract negotiations. Johnson felt he was due a considerably larger sum of money.  As the leading rusher since 2008 (4,598 yards) he was set to make $1.065 million in 2011, under existing contract terms (approximately 10% of the money paid to the second-place rusher for the same period).<ref>{{cite news |title=Tennessee Titans are ready to pay Chris Johnson \u2014 as soon as he shows up to camp |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/early-lead/post/tennessee-titans-are-ready-to-pay-chris-johnson--as-soon-as-he-shows-up-to-camp/2011/08/12/gIQAUOx1AJ_blog.html |work=Washington Post |date=August 12, 2011 |accessdate=}}</ref> On September 1, Johnson became the highest paid running back in the NFL, agreeing to a four-year, $53.5 million contract extension through to the 2016 season, including $30 million guaranteed, with the Titans, ending his holdout.<ref>{{cite news|title=Chris Johnson signs $53.5 million extension with Titans |url=http://aol.sportingnews.com/nfl/story/2011-09-01/chris-johnson-re-signs-with-titans-for-535-million |work=Sporting News |publisher=aol.sportingnews.com |date=September 1, 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn early November, a report surfaced that Johnson could be released by the Titans prior to the fifth day of the 2012 league year, which begins every March.<ref name=\"release\">{{cite web|url=http://profootballtalk.nbcsports.com/2011/11/06/teams-wonder-whether-chris-johnson-will-be-a-free-agent/ |title=Teams wonder whether Chris Johnson will be a free agent |publisher=Pro Football Talk |date=November 6, 2011 |accessdate=November 6, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6309XU1ED?url=http://profootballtalk.nbcsports.com/2011/11/06/teams-wonder-whether-chris-johnson-will-be-a-free-agent/ |archivedate=November 6, 2011 }}</ref> At the time of the report, Johnson was having the worst season of his career with just 302 rushing yards and one touchdown on 107 carries through the season's first seven games. Johnson's contract calls for an $8 million salary in 2012 that became guaranteed in March; he also will receive a guaranteed salary of $9 million since the fifth day of the 2013 league year passed. If the Titans had released Johnson prior the March 2012 deadline, they would have saved $17 million and Johnson would have become a free agent. On November 13, he had 130 rushing yards and a rushing touchdown against the Carolina Panthers.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201111130car.htm |title=Tennessee Titans at Carolina Panthers - November 13th, 2011 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=March 17, 2018}}</ref> Two weeks later, he had 190 rushing yards against the Tampa Bay Buccaneers.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201111270oti.htm |title=Tampa Bay Buccaneers at Tennessee Titans - November 27th, 2011 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=March 17, 2018}}</ref> in the next game, against the Buffalo Bills, he had 153 rushing yards and two rushing touchdowns.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201112040buf.htm |title=Tennessee Titans at Buffalo Bills - December 4th, 2011 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=March 17, 2018}}</ref>\n\nDuring the 2011 season, Johnson struggled throughout the season under offensive coordinator Chris Palmer. However, he still finished with 1,047 rushing yards and four rushing touchdowns.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/J/JohnCh04/gamelog/2011/ |title=Chris Johnson 2011 Game Log |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=March 17, 2018}}</ref> After a frustrating season, Johnson elected to participate in the Titans' off-season training program in preparation for the 2012 season.\n\n====2012 season====\n{{See also|2012 Tennessee Titans season}}\n\nAfter participating in the Titan summer training camp prior to the 2012 season, Johnson initially struggled during his first two games of the 2012 season gaining just 21 yards on a total of 19 rushing attempts, highlighted by an 11 carry, 4-yard effort against the [[New England Patriots]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201209090oti.htm |title=New England Patriots at Tennessee Titans - September 9th, 2012 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=March 17, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201209160sdg.htm |title=Tennessee Titans at San Diego Chargers - September 16th, 2012 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=March 17, 2018}}</ref> During recent interviews, Johnson appeared to be frustrated with the new direction Titan's offensive coordinator [[Chris Palmer (American football)|Chris Palmer]] is running, electing to bring a more run-and-shoot offensive scheme to the Titans and not focusing on establishing the rushing attack. Palmer was fired later on in the season. In week 4, he finally showed his abilities with 25 carries for 141 yards, but Tennessee still lost 38-14.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201209300htx.htm |title=Tennessee Titans at Houston Texans - September 30th, 2012 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=March 17, 2018}}</ref> He followed that up with only 24 yards on 15 carries against the [[Minnesota Vikings]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201210070min.htm |title=Tennessee Titans at Minnesota Vikings - October 7th, 2012 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=March 17, 2018}}</ref> On ''[[Thursday Night Football]]'', he ran for 91 yards on 19 carries against the [[Pittsburgh Steelers]] in a 26-23 victory.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201210110oti.htm |title=Pittsburgh Steelers at Tennessee Titans - October 11th, 2012 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=March 17, 2018}}</ref> He followed that up with a great game against the [[Buffalo Bills]] in which he ran for 195 yards and 2 touchdowns on only 18 carries. With an 83-yard touchdown, Johnson broke an NFL record with his fourth rushing touchdown of 80 yards or more. The [[Tennessee Titans]] won the game 35-34.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201210210buf.htm |title=Tennessee Titans at Buffalo Bills - October 21st, 2012 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=March 17, 2018}}</ref> He then ran for 99 yards on 21 carries in an overtime loss to the [[Indianapolis Colts]], 19-13.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201210280oti.htm |title=Indianapolis Colts at Tennessee Titans - October 28th, 2012 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=March 17, 2018}}</ref> He got off to a relatively slow start against the [[Chicago Bears]], fumbling twice. In the fourth quarter, he ran for an 80-yard touchdown, extending his record with his fifth 80-yard touchdowns. He finished with 16 carries for 141 yards, but the Titans still lost 51-20.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201211040oti.htm |title=Chicago Bears at Tennessee Titans - November 4th, 2012 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=March 17, 2018}}</ref> In the next game, he ran for 126 yards on 23 carries and a 17-yard touchdown ending the [[Miami Dolphins]] streak of 22 consecutive games without allowing a 100-yard rusher.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201211110mia.htm |title=Tennessee Titans at Miami Dolphins - November 11th, 2012 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=March 17, 2018}}</ref> He then ran for 80 yards on 21 carries against the [[Jacksonville Jaguars]], however the Titans lost 24-19.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201211250jax.htm |title=Tennessee Titans at Jacksonville Jaguars - November 25th, 2012 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=March 17, 2018}}</ref> In the next week against the [[Houston Texans]], he got a 26-yard run on Tennessee's opening drive but finished with only 51 yards on 13 carries.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201212020oti.htm |title=Houston Texans at Tennessee Titans - December 2nd, 2012 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=March 17, 2018}}</ref> After the game, he said he was frustrated with the lack of carries. In week 14 against the [[Indianapolis Colts|Colts]] he struggled to get anything going only running for 44 yards on 19 carries.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201212090clt.htm |title=Tennessee Titans at Indianapolis Colts - December 9th, 2012 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=March 17, 2018}}</ref> In week 15 on ''[[Monday Night Football]]'', Johnson had a franchise-record 94-yard touchdown run, the longest of his career and the second longest in ''Monday Night Football'' history. He finished with 122 yards on 21 carries. The Titans beat the [[New York Jets]] 14-10.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201212170oti.htm |title=New York Jets at Tennessee Titans - December 17th, 2012 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=March 17, 2018}}</ref> Overall, he finished the 2012 season with 1,243 rushing yards and six rushing touchdowns.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/J/JohnCh04/gamelog/2012/ |title=Chris Johnson 2012 Game Log |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=March 17, 2018}}</ref>\n\n====2013 season====\n{{See also|2013 Tennessee Titans season}}\n\nJohnson started the 2013 season with 25 carries for 70 yards in a 16\u20139 victory over the Pittsburgh Steelers.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201309080pit.htm |title=Tennessee Titans at Pittsburgh Steelers - September 8th, 2013 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=March 17, 2018}}</ref> On November 3, against the St. Louis Rams, he had 150 rushing yards and two rushing touchdowns.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201311030ram.htm |title=Tennessee Titans at St. Louis Rams - November 3rd, 2013 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=March 17, 2018}}</ref> On November 14, he had 86 rushing yards and two rushing touchdowns against the Indianapolis Colts.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201311140oti.htm |title=Indianapolis Colts at Tennessee Titans - November 14th, 2013 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=March 17, 2018}}</ref> In the regular season finale against the Houston Texans, he had 127 rushing yards and a rushing touchdown in the 16\u201310 victory.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201312290oti.htm |title=Houston Texans at Tennessee Titans - December 29th, 2013 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=March 17, 2018}}</ref> He rushed for 1,077 yards on 279 carries with six touchdowns in 16 games. The 2013 season was less productive statistically for Johnson than any other year of his career up to that point.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/J/JohnCh04/gamelog/2013/ |title=Chris Johnson 2013 Game Log |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=March 17, 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn April 4, 2014, the Titans released Johnson.<ref>[http://espn.go.com/nfl/story/_/id/10726980/tennessee-titans-release-chris-johnson]. ESPN.com. Retrieved on April 4, 2014.</ref>\n\n===New York Jets===\n====2014 season====\n{{See also|2014 New York Jets season}}\n\nJohnson agreed to a three-year contract worth $9 million per year with the [[New York Jets]] on April 16, 2014.<ref>{{cite web|title=Chris Johnson lands with Jets |url=http://espn.go.com/new-york/nfl/story/_/id/10791328/chris-johnson-agrees-two-year-deal-new-york-jets |publisher=ESPN New York |author=Cimini, Rich |date=April 16, 2014 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6OstRBhIV?url=http://espn.go.com/new-york/nfl/story/_/id/10791328/chris-johnson-agrees-two-year-deal-new-york-jets |archivedate=April 16, 2014 |accessdate=April 16, 2014 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Johnson finished the 2014 season with 153 carries for a career-low 663 yards and one touchdown.<ref name=\"Jets end\">{{cite web|work=ESPN.com|url=http://espn.go.com/newyork/nfl/story/_/id/12325220/new-york-jets-decline-exercise-chris-johnson-option-bonus|title=Jets decline Chris Johnson option|date=February 15, 2015|accessdate=March 17, 2016|first=Rich|last=Cimini}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/J/JohnCh04/gamelog/2014/ |title=Chris Johnson 2014 Game Log |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=March 17, 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe Jets declined the second year of Johnson's contract on February 15, 2015 making him a free agent in the 2015 offseason.<ref name=\"Jets end\"/>\n\n===Arizona Cardinals===\n====2015 season: Resurgent season====\n{{See also|2015 Arizona Cardinals season}}\n\nOn August 17, 2015, Johnson agreed to a one-year, $2.56 million contract with the [[Arizona Cardinals]].<ref>{{cite web|work=NFL.com|url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000511185/article/arizona-cardinals-sign-running-back-chris-johnson|title=Arizona Cardinals sign running back Chris Johnson|first=Gregg|last=Rosenthal|date=August 17, 2015|accessdate=August 17, 2015}}</ref> Johnson was having a great season and was in the top three in rushing yards for more than half of the season, looking like his great past performance in Tennessee. Some of his notable games included a 110-yard, two-touchdown performance against the San Francisco 49ers and 122 yards, and on October 26, a touchdown against the Baltimore Ravens.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201509270crd.htm |title=San Francisco 49ers at Arizona Cardinals - September 27th, 2015 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=March 17, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201510260crd.htm |title=Baltimore Ravens at Arizona Cardinals - October 26th, 2015 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=March 17, 2018}}</ref> On November 29, 2015, Johnson suffered a fractured tibia during the Week 12 matchup against the [[San Francisco 49ers]].<ref>{{cite web|work=NFL.com|url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000591771/article/chris-johnson-out-indefinitely-with-fractured-tibia|title=Chris Johnson (fractured tibia) placed on IR boomerang|first=Chris|last=Wesseling|date=December 1, 2015|accessdate=March 17, 2016}}</ref> He was then placed on the injured reserve with a designation to return list on December 1, 2015.<ref>{{cite web|title=Chris Johnson on IR with fractured tibia, but could return for Super Bowl|url=http://espn.go.com/nfl/story/_/id/14268158/chris-johnson-arizona-cardinals-placed-ir-return-team-makes-super-bowl|publisher=ESPN|accessdate=December 2, 2015}}</ref> Johnson finished the 2015 regular season with 196 carries for 814 yards and three touchdowns, along with being named a Pro Bowl alternate.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/J/JohnCh04/gamelog/2015/ |title=Chris Johnson 2015 Game Log |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=March 17, 2018}}</ref>\n\n====2016 season====\n{{See also|2016 Arizona Cardinals season}}\n\nJohnson re-signed with the Cardinals on a one-year, $3 million contract on March 17, 2016.<ref>{{cite web|work=NFL.com|url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000645352/article/cardinals-chris-johnson-strike-oneyear-deal|title=Cardinals, Chris Johnson strike one-year deal|first=Marc|last=Sessler|date=March 17, 2016|accessdate=March 17, 2016}}</ref> The emergence of [[David Johnson (running back)|David Johnson]] as a star running back for the Cardinals limited Chris Johnson's use. On October 4, 2016, he was placed on injured reserve with a groin injury.<ref>{{cite web|title=Chris Johnson, Tyvon Branch To IR; Butler Cut|url=http://www.azcardinals.com/news-and-events/article-2/Chris-Johnson-Tyvon-Branch-To-IR-Butler-Cut/a3a64d8b-e7f6-4089-869e-81f4217dd19d|author=Urban, Darren|website=AZCardinals.com|date=October 4, 2016|access-date=October 4, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161005124803/http://www.azcardinals.com/news-and-events/article-2/Chris-Johnson-Tyvon-Branch-To-IR-Butler-Cut/a3a64d8b-e7f6-4089-869e-81f4217dd19d|archive-date=October 5, 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref> He finished the season with 95 rushing yards and a rushing touchdown.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/J/JohnCh04/gamelog/2016/ |title=Chris Johnson 2016 Game Log |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=March 17, 2018}}</ref>\n\n====2017 season====\n{{See also|2017 Arizona Cardinals season}}\n\nOn July 20, 2017, the Cardinals re-signed Johnson on a one-year contract.<ref>{{cite web|title=Cardinals re-sign Chris Johnson to one-year contract|url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000821014/article/cardinals-resign-chris-johnson-to-oneyear-deal|author=Wesseling, Chris|website=NFL.com|date=July 20, 2017}}</ref> He was released on September 1, 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000838616/article/chris-johnson-cut-by-arizona-cardinals|title=Chris Johnson cut by Arizona Cardinals|first=Kevin |last=Patra|website=NFL.com|date=September 1, 2017|accessdate=September 1, 2017}}</ref> On September 12, 2017, Johnson re-signed with the [[Arizona Cardinals]].<ref>{{cite web|title=David Johnson To IR As Chris Johnson Returns|url=http://www.azcardinals.com/news-and-events/article-2/David-Johnson-To-IR-As-Chris-Johnson-Returns/f88211f1-baf5-4e45-9b53-3d4b016d4e51|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171110233600/http://www.azcardinals.com/news-and-events/article-2/David-Johnson-To-IR-As-Chris-Johnson-Returns/f88211f1-baf5-4e45-9b53-3d4b016d4e51|url-status=dead|archive-date=November 10, 2017|author=Urban, Darren|website=AZCardinals.com|date=September 12, 2017}}</ref>\n\nJohnson was released by the team on October 10, 2017.<ref>{{cite web|title=Cardinals release veteran RB Chris Johnson|url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000859548/article/cardinals-release-veteran-rb-chris-johnson|author=Shook, Nick|website=NFL.com|date=October 10, 2017}}</ref> He had played in four games in the 2017 season and had 114 rushing yards.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/J/JohnCh04/gamelog/2017/ |title=Chris Johnson 2017 Game Log |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=March 17, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Retirement===\nOn November 5, 2018, Johnson announced his retirement from the NFL after 10 seasons in the league.<ref>{{cite web|title=Veteran RB Chris Johnson retires after 10 seasons|url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000984911/article/veteran-rb-chris-johnson-retires-after-10-seasons|author=Teope, Herbie|website=NFL.com|date=November 5, 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn April 24, 2019, Johnson signed a one-day contract to retire as a member of the Tennessee Titans.<ref>{{cite web|title=Chris Johnson Will Sign a One-Day Contract to Retire as a Titan on Wednesday in Nashville|url=https://www.titansonline.com/news/chris-johnson-will-sign-a-one-day-contract-to-retire-as-a-titan-on-wednesday-in-|author=Wyatt, Jim|website=TitansOnline.com|date=April 24, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===NFL statistics===\n====Regular season====\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n| colspan=\"2\"|<center>Legend</center>\n|-\n| style=\"background:#cfecec; width:3em;\"| \n| Led the league\n|}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\"| Year\n! rowspan=\"2\"| Team\n! colspan=\"2\"| Games\n! colspan=\"5\"| Rushing\n! colspan=\"4\"| Receiving\n! colspan=\"2\"| Fumbles\n|-\n! GP !! GS !! Att !! Yds !! Avg !! Lng !! TD !! Rec !! Yds !! Lng !! TD !! Fum !! Lost\n|-\n! [[2008 NFL season|2008]] || [[2008 Tennessee Titans season|TEN]] \n| 15 || 14 || 251 || 1,228 || 4.9 || 66T || 9 || 43 || 260 || 25 || 