ing\n! colspan=\"4\"| Receiving\n! colspan=\"2\"| Fumbles\n|-\n! GP !! GS !! Att !! Yds !! Avg !! Lng !! TD !! Rec !! Yds !! Lng !! TD !! Fum !! Lost\n|-\n! [[2008 NFL season|2008]] !! [[2008 Tennessee Titans season|TEN]] \n| 1 || 1 || 11 || 72 || 6.5 || 32 || 1 || 1 || 28 || 28 || 0 || 0 || 0\n|-\n!colspan=\"2\"|Career !! 1 !! 1 !! 11 !! 72 !! 6.5 !! 32 !! 1 !! 1 !! 28 !! 28 !! 0 !! 0 !! 0\n|-\n|}\n\n''Source: [http://www.nfl.com/player/chrisjohnson/262/careerstats NFL.com]''\n\n===NFL records===\n* Only player in NFL history with a touchdown of 50 yards, 60 yards, and 90 yards in one game. (a 57-yard rush, a 69-yard reception, and a 91-yard rush during Week 2 against the Texans, 2009)\n* Most total scrimmage yards in one single season: 2,509 (2009)\n* Most total scrimmage yards in one month: 968 (November 2009)\n* Only player in NFL history with 6 touchdown runs of over 80 yards (80, 83, 85, 89, 91, 94). No other player has more than four.\n* Only player in NFL history with 4 touchdown runs of over 85 yards (85, 89, 91, 94).\n* Only player in NFL history to run for three 80-yard touchdown runs in a single season on more than one occasion (2009, 2012). \n* First player in NFL history with 6 consecutive games of 125+ rushing yards and a 5.0+ yards per carry average (Breaking [[Jim Brown]]'s record set in 1958 of five consecutive games).\n* First player in NFL history with at least 1,900 rushing yards and 400 receiving yards in the same season (2009)\n* First player in NFL history with at least 1,900 rushing yards and 50 receptions in the same season (2009)\n* Second most consecutive games rushing for more than 100 yards (12, 10/18/09 - 9/12/10, first is Barry Sanders with 14).\n* One of two players to have 2,000 rushing yard in a season but under 10,000 in a career (other is Terrell Davis).\n\n====Titans franchise records====\n* Most rushing yards in a single season: 2,006\n\n==Personal life==\nIn the early morning of March 8, 2015, Johnson was shot in the shoulder during a drive-by in [[Orlando, Florida]] in which the driver of the vehicle, Dreekius Oricko Johnson, was killed. Reggie Johnson, who also was in the car, sustained injuries to the shoulder, leg, and hand.<ref>{{cite news|work=USAToday.com|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/nfl/2015/03/08/chris-johnson-shot-arm-friend-dead-florida/24608321/|title=Former Jets RB Chris Johnson shot in Florida; one dead|first=Jim|last=Corbett|date=March 8, 2015|accessdate=March 17, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 2013, Johnson appeared on an episode of ''[[Ink Master]]'' as a special guest judge. Before the 2013 NFL season, Johnson participated in the National Geographic\u2019s \u201cMan v. Cheetah\u201d documentary. On the show Johnson raced a [[cheetah]] on a 220-foot-long course with a wall separating them. The cheetah won.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://todaysloser.com/chris-johnson-loses-his-race-against-a-cheetah/ |title=Archived copy |accessdate=December 28, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131230235030/http://todaysloser.com/chris-johnson-loses-his-race-against-a-cheetah/ |archivedate=December 30, 2013 }}</ref>\n\n==Legal issues==\nOn June 12, 2018, it was revealed per TMZ that Johnson had allegedly attacked and choked a business valet in Tampa, Florida, dating back to April of the same year.<ref>{{cite news |title=Chris Johnson charged with attacking valet |url=https://www.tmz.com/2018/06/11/chris-johnson-battery-arrest-surveillance-video/ |work=TMZ |accessdate=June 12, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Chris Johnson facing misdemeanor battery charge |url=http://www.espn.com/nfl/story/_/id/23761140/free-agent-rb-chris-johnson-facing-misdemeanor-battery-charge-stemming-april-9-incident-florida |publisher=ESPN |accessdate=June 12, 2018}}</ref>\nDuring the cvid19 lockdown in April 2020 it was revealed that Chris Johnson was involved in funding a gang-related murder for hire plot in retaliation for a friend being murdered and Johnson himself receiving a shot to the shoulder in 2015\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n*{{Official website}}\n*{{NFL.com player}}\n*{{ESPN NFL}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20071127015647/http://ecupirates.cstv.com/sports/m-footbl/mtt/johnson_chris00.html East Carolina Pirates bio]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20090918043547/http://www.titansonline.com/team/roster/chris-johnson/845a0bae-872b-40f5-9822-5e346f78edc7 Tennessee Titans bio]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20140622112042/http://www.newyorkjets.com/team/roster/chris-johnson/e1927d86-cb30-4993-9790-cc15465596f2/ New York Jets bio]\n\n{{Navboxes\n| title = Chris Johnson\u2014awards and honors\n| list =\n{{2008 NFL Draft}}\n{{TitansFirstPick}}\n{{Titans2008DraftPicks}}\n{{AP Offensive Players of the Year}}\n{{FedEx NFL Players}}\n{{NFL rushing yards leaders}}\n{{NFL 2000 Yard Rushers}}\n}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Johnson, Chris}}\n[[Category:1985 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:African-American players of American football]]\n[[Category:American football running backs]]\n[[Category:American shooting survivors]]\n[[Category:Arizona Cardinals players]]\n[[Category:East Carolina Pirates football players]]\n[[Category:New York Jets players]]\n[[Category:Players of American football from Florida]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Orlando, Florida]]\n[[Category:Tennessee Titans players]]\n", "text_old": "{{other people|Chris Johnson}}\n{{short description|American football running back}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2019}}\n{{Infobox NFL biography\n|name=Chris Johnson \n|image=Chris Johnson sitting on his helmet.jpg\n|image_size=\n|alt=\n|caption=Johnson with the Tennessee Titans in 2010\n|number=28, 21, 27, 23\n|position=[[Running back]]\n|birth_date={{Birth date and age|1985|9|23|mf=y}}\n|birth_place=[[Orlando, Florida]]\n|death_date=\n|death_place=\n|height_ft=5\n|height_in=11\n|weight_lbs=203\n|high_school=[[Olympia High School (Orlando, Florida)|Olympia]] ([[Orlando, Florida]])\n|college=[[East Carolina Pirates football|East Carolina]]\n|draftyear=2008\n|draftround=1\n|draftpick=24\n|pastteams=\n* [[Tennessee Titans]] ({{NFL Year|2008}}\u2013{{NFL Year|2013}})\n* [[New York Jets]] ({{NFL Year|2014}})\n* [[Arizona Cardinals]] ({{NFL Year|2015}}\u2013{{NFL Year|2017}})\n|status=\n|highlights=\n* 3\u00d7 [[Pro Bowl]] ([[2009 Pro Bowl|2008]]\u2013[[2011 Pro Bowl|2010]])\n* First-team [[All-Pro]] ([[2009 All-Pro Team|2009]])\n* [[National Football League Offensive Player of the Year Award|NFL Offensive Player of the Year]] (2009)\n* [[NFL rushing champions|NFL rushing yards leader]] (2009)\n* 2\u00d7 First-team All-[[Conference USA|C-USA]] (2006, 2007)\n;NFL record \n*2,509 yards from scrimmage, season\n|statweek=\n|statseason=\n|statlabel1=[[Rushing yards]]\n|statvalue1=9,651\n|statlabel2=[[Average|Rushing average]]\n|statvalue2=4.5\n|statlabel3=[[Touchdown|Rushing touchdowns]]\n|statvalue3=55\n|statlabel4=[[Reception (American football)|Receptions]]\n|statvalue4=307\n|statlabel5=[[Receiving yards]]\n|statvalue5=2,255\n|statlabel6=[[Touchdown|Receiving touchdowns]]\n|statvalue6=9\n|nflnew=chrisjohnson/262\n}}\n'''Christopher Duan Johnson''' (born September 23, 1985) is a former [[American football]] [[running back]]. Born in [[Orlando, Florida]], Johnson emerged as a senior for [[East Carolina University]] where he broke out for 2,960 all-purpose yards and 24 touchdowns. He was drafted by the [[Tennessee Titans]] in the first round of the [[2008 NFL Draft]], after running a then-record breaking 4.24 seconds in the [[40-yard dash]] at the [[NFL Combine]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Top Five Fastest Players in the NFL|url=https://sports.yahoo.com/nfl/news?slug=ycn-9163571|work=Yahoo|accessdate=September 22, 2012|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130719022231/http://sports.yahoo.com/nfl/news?slug=ycn-9163571|archivedate=July 19, 2013}}</ref> In 2009, he won the [[List of NFL rushing champions|NFL rushing title]] with 2,006 yards (the sixth of only seven players ever to gain over 2,000 in a season), and broke [[Marshall Faulk]]'s record of total [[yards from scrimmage]] with 2,509.<ref name=\"sixth\">{{Citation |url=http://sports.espn.go.com/nfl/news/story?id=4793132 |title=Tennessee Titans' Chris Johnson sixth to join 2,000-rushing-yard club |work=ESPN |date=January 3, 2010 }}</ref> This earned him the nickname '''CJ2K'''. He has been to three [[Pro Bowl]]s and was the NFL's [[National Football League Offensive Player of the Year Award|Offensive Player of the Year]] in 2009. Johnson has also played for the [[New York Jets]] and [[Arizona Cardinals]].\n\n==Early years==\nJohnson was born in Orlando, Florida, on September 23, 1985. He played [[high school football|football]] at [[Olympia High School (Orlando, Florida)|Olympia High School]] in Orlando.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://articles.orlandosentinel.com/2008-10-14/sports/sowens14_1_johnson-olympia-high-grades |title=Former Olympia football star Chris Johnson excels in life |work=Orlando Sentinel |access-date=March 17, 2018 |language=en}}</ref> Considered only a two-star recruit by [[Rivals.com]], Johnson was not ranked among the nation's top running back prospects in 2004.<ref>{{cite web | title=Chris Johnson Profile | url=https://footballrecruiting.rivals.com/viewprospect.asp?pr_key=21370 | work=Rivals.com | publisher= | date= | accessdate= }}</ref>  He selected East Carolina over [[Eastern Kentucky University|Eastern Kentucky]] and [[University of Connecticut|UConn]].\n\n===Track and field===\nJohnson was also a standout track star at [[Olympia High School (Orlando, Florida)|Olympia High School]]. In his senior year, he finished second in the [[100 metres]] at the 2004 Florida 4A state championships behind [[Walter Dix]].<ref>[http://FL.milesplit.us/meets/5423/results/14902 FHSAA 3A-4A Outdoor State Finals- 4A Boys Complete Results \u2013 flrunners.com] {{Webarchive|url=https://archive.today/20120708170020/http://fl.milesplit.us/meets/5423/results/14902 |date=July 8, 2012 }}. Fl.milesplit.us. Retrieved on June 2, 2012.</ref> In addition, Johnson also finished his senior season posting personal bests of 10.38 <ref>[http://www.trackandfieldnews.com/lists/2004/prep_out_m.html Track & Field News: Lists: 2004: Men's High School] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091011101925/http://www.trackandfieldnews.com/lists/2004/prep_out_m.html |date=October 11, 2009 }}. Trackandfieldnews.com. Retrieved on June 2, 2012.</ref> and 21.28 (the nation's 24th fastest in 2004) in the [[100 metres]] and [[200 metres]] respectively.\n\nIn his junior year, he qualified for the finals of the Florida State meet with a preliminary time of 10.83 seconds. Walter Dix won the event with a 10.46 in the finals, Johnson placed 4th with a time of 10.66. He anchored the [[4 \u00d7 100 meters relay]] team that won Golden South and Golden West National Championships.\n\nHis personal bests are 10.38 seconds<ref>http://www.all-athletics.com/node/88468</ref> in the [[100 meters]] and 21.28 seconds in the [[200 meters]].<ref>http://fl.milesplit.com/meets/5423/results/14902</ref>\n\n==College career==\n\n===2004 season===\n\n{{See also|2004 East Carolina Pirates football team}}\n\nJohnson enrolled in [[East Carolina University]], majoring in Communications <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.titansonline.com/team/roster/chris-johnson/845a0bae-872b-40f5-9822-5e346f78edc7/|title=Chris Johnson|work=titansonline.com|accessdate=February 19, 2018}}</ref> and was a member of the [[East Carolina Pirates football]] team.  He made an immediate impact in all 11 games, as he eventually started seven games on the season.  He finished the season on the [[Conference USA]] All-Freshman squad as a running back. He recorded a reception in 10 straight games which was a team-best. He finished the season with 561 yards rushing and 765 yards on kick returns for 1,562 all-purpose yards, all team-highs. He finished the season by being ranked 24th nationally for all-purpose yardage, and also rushed for five touchdowns.  He finished the season with eight school game or season records for a freshman and finished the year with 32 catches for 236 yards and two touchdowns, second on the team.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/players/chris-johnson-1/gamelog/2004/ |title=Chris Johnson 2004 Game Log |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=March 17, 2018}}</ref> In his collegiate debut against [[West Virginia Mountaineers football|West Virginia]], Johnson returned five kickoffs for a total of 100 yards.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/boxscores/2004-09-04-west-virginia.html |title=East Carolina at West Virginia Box Score, September 4, 2004 |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=March 17, 2018}}</ref> Against [[2004 Louisville Cardinals football team|Louisville]], Johnson returned seven kickoffs for 102 yards.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/boxscores/2004-10-02-louisville.html |title=East Carolina at Louisville Box Score, October 2, 2004 |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=March 17, 2018}}</ref> In a victory over [[Tulane Green Wave football|Tulane]], he set season-highs with 31 carries for 158 yards and two scores.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/boxscores/2004-10-09-east-carolina.html |title=Tulane at East Carolina Box Score, October 9, 2004 |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=March 17, 2018}}</ref> Against [[South Florida Bulls football|South Florida]], Johnson totaled 212 all-purpose yards and scored ECU's only offensive touchdown on an 18-yard reception.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/boxscores/2004-11-13-south-florida.html |title=East Carolina at South Florida Box Score, November 13, 2004 |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=March 17, 2018}}</ref> In the season finale against [[NC State Wolfpack football|NC State]], Johnson totaled a season-high 144 kickoff return yards.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/boxscores/2004-11-27-east-carolina.html |title=North Carolina State vs East Carolina Box Score, November 27, 2004 |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=March 17, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===2005 season===\n\n{{See also|2005 East Carolina Pirates football team}}\n\nAfter his memorable freshman season, Johnson started all 11 games at tailback in his sophomore season. He led the team with 684 yards on 176 carries and six touchdowns, while also recording 35 receptions for 356 yards and two scores and 459 kickoff return yards. He was also the team leader with 1,499 all-purpose yards and set a school record with 67 career receptions as a running back.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/schools/east-carolina/2005.html |title=2005 East Carolina Pirates Stats |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=March 17, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/players/chris-johnson-1/gamelog/2005/ |title=Chris Johnson 2005 Game Log |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=March 17, 2018}}</ref> Against the West Virginia Mountaineers, Johnson rushed for 92 yards on 22 carries, both team highs.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/boxscores/2005-09-24-west-virginia.html |title=East Carolina at West Virginia Box Score, September 24, 2005 |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=March 17, 2018}}</ref> In the [[Southern Miss Golden Eagles football|Southern Mississippi]] game, Johnson returned four kickoffs for 100 yards.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/boxscores/2005-10-01-east-carolina.html |title=Southern Mississippi at East Carolina Box Score, October 1, 2005 |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=March 17, 2018}}</ref> In the [[Rice Owls football|Rice]] victory, Johnson totaled 129 receiving yards, including an 81-yard touchdown reception.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/boxscores/2005-10-08-east-carolina.html |title=Rice at East Carolina Box Score, October 8, 2005 |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=March 17, 2018}}</ref> His 100-yard receiving game teamed-up with [[Aundrae Allison]]'s 109 yards marked the first dual 100-yard receiving game since 1999 for the Pirates. In the [[Tulsa Golden Hurricane football|Tulsa]] game, Johnson did not record a reception which ended his consecutive streak at 18 games.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/boxscores/2005-11-12-tulsa.html |title=East Carolina at Tulsa Box Score, November 12, 2005 |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=March 17, 2018}}</ref> However, in the following game against [[Marshall Thundering Herd football|Marshall]], Johnson carried the ball 18 times for 106 yards and a career-high 3 touchdowns.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/boxscores/2005-11-19-marshall.html |title=East Carolina at Marshall Box Score, November 19, 2005 |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=March 17, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===2006 season===\n\n{{See also|2006 East Carolina Pirates football team}}\n\nAfter missing spring practice due to neck surgery, Johnson returned in his junior season with 972 all-purpose yards. In the down season, Johnson totaled 314 rushing yards, 176 receiving yards, and 482 kickoff return yards.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/players/chris-johnson-1/gamelog/2006/ |title=Chris Johnson 2006 Game Log |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=March 17, 2018}}</ref> He played in 12 games on the season but only started five. He was selected to the All-Conference USA first-team as a return specialist after the season. He also broke the school career record for receiving yards as a running back with 768 yards, but only had one 100-yard rushing game on the year and only had four rushing scores. In the season opener, against [[Navy Midshipmen football|Navy]], Johnson only recorded 54 all-purpose yards with one rushing touchdown.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/boxscores/2006-09-02-navy.html |title=East Carolina at Navy Box Score, September 2, 2006 |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=March 17, 2018}}</ref> In the [[UAB]] game, Johnson had 112 all-purpose yards.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/boxscores/2006-09-09-alabama-birmingham.html |title=East Carolina at UAB Box Score, September 9, 2006 |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=March 17, 2018}}</ref> In the [[Memphis Tigers football|Memphis]] game, Johnson recorded his only 100-yard rushing game with 106 yards on 22 carries for two touchdowns. He finished the game with 180 all-purpose yards.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/boxscores/2006-09-16-east-carolina.html |title=Memphis at East Carolina Box Score, September 16, 2006 |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=March 17, 2018}}</ref> Johnson had a foot injury that limited his action in the West Virginia game, and caused him to miss the [[2006 Virginia Cavaliers football team|Virginia]] game. In the [[SMU Mustangs football|SMU]] game, Johnson returned a kickoff for a career-long 51 yards.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/boxscores/2006-10-21-east-carolina.html |title=SMU at East Carolina Box Score, October 21, 2006 |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=March 17, 2018}}</ref> Then, in the Southern Miss game, Johnson recorded 136 all-purpose yards that included a 96-yard kickoff return for a touchdown, his second career return touchdown.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/boxscores/2006-10-28-southern-mississippi.html |title=East Carolina at Southern Mississippi Box Score, October 28, 2006 |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=March 17, 2018}}</ref> The return also made national recognition on [[ESPN]]'s top plays. Against Rice, Johnson carried the ball 12 times for 83 yards.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/boxscores/2006-11-18-rice.html |title=East Carolina at Rice Box Score, November 18, 2006 |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=March 17, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===2007 season===\n\n{{See also|2007 East Carolina Pirates football team}}\n\n[[File:2007 Hawaii Bowl - Boise State University vs East Carolina University - Chris Johnson.jpg|thumb|right|Johnson rushing the ball on a play during the [[2007 Hawaii Bowl]].]]\nAfter an average junior season, Johnson entered his senior season as a preseason All-Conference USA first-team as a return specialist. However, he finished the season as a first-team selection as returner and second-team selection as a running back. Johnson began the season with a rushing score in the 17\u20137 loss to [[2007 Virginia Tech Hokies football team|Virginia Tech]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/boxscores/2007-09-01-virginia-tech.html |title=East Carolina at Virginia Tech Box Score, September 1, 2007 |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=March 17, 2018}}</ref> He followed that performance up with a career-high 136 yards on 5 receptions for two touchdowns, including a 78-yard touchdown reception, and also a rushing touchdown against [[2007 North Carolina Tar Heels football team|North Carolina]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/boxscores/2007-09-08-east-carolina.html |title=North Carolina at East Carolina Box Score, September 8, 2007 |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=March 17, 2018}}</ref> In the 48\u20137 loss to West Virginia, Johnson rushed for 76 yards on 14 carries and also scored ECU's only touchdown of the game.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/boxscores/2007-09-22-west-virginia.html |title=East Carolina at West Virginia Box Score, September 22, 2007 |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=March 17, 2018}}</ref> After a slow start rushing on the season, Johnson rushed for 147 yards on 24 carries with two touchdowns against [[University of Houston|Houston]] in the 37\u201335 victory.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/boxscores/2007-09-29-houston.html |title=East Carolina at Houston Box Score, September 29, 2007 |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=March 17, 2018}}</ref> In the [[2007 UCF Knights football team|Central Florida]] victory, Johnson rushed for 89 yards with two scores, caught 5 receptions for 89 yards and a touchdown, and returned four kickoffs for 194 yards with a 96-yard touchdown return. He finished the game with a then career-high 272 all-purpose yards and four touchdowns.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/boxscores/2007-10-06-east-carolina.html |title=UCF at East Carolina Box Score, October 6, 2007 |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=March 17, 2018}}</ref> The next game, against [[2007 UTEP Miners football team|UTEP]], Johnson rushed for 126 yards on 23 carries.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/boxscores/2007-10-13-texas-el-paso.html |title=East Carolina at UTEP Box Score, October 13, 2007 |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=March 17, 2018}}</ref> Then, in the 56\u201340 victory over Memphis, Johnson rushed for a career-high 301 yards and four touchdowns. He also had four kick returns for 95 yards for a then career-high 396 all-purpose yards and four touchdowns in the game.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/boxscores/2007-11-03-memphis.html |title=East Carolina at Memphis Box Score, November 3, 2007 |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=March 17, 2018}}</ref> In the following loss to Marshall, Johnson rushed for 72 yards and a score and 45 receiving yards for a total of 117 all-purpose yards.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/boxscores/2007-11-10-marshall.html |title=East Carolina at Marshall Box Score, November 10, 2007 |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=March 17, 2018}}</ref> Then, in the 35\u201312 victory over Tulane, Johnson rushed for 155 yards on 27 carries for two scores and caught four passes for 85 yards and another score for 240 all-purpose yards and three scores.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/boxscores/2007-11-24-east-carolina.html |title=Tulane at East Carolina Box Score, November 24, 2007 |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=March 17, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn Johnson's final collegiate game, the [[2007 Hawai'i Bowl]] against [[2007 Boise State Broncos football team|Boise State]], Johnson rushed for 223 yards on 28 carries and a touchdown as the Pirates won, 41\u201338. Johnson also had three receptions for 32 yards and a score and had six kick returns for 153 yards for a career-high and NCAA FBS record of 408 [[all-purpose yards]] and two scores.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/boxscores/2007-12-23-boise-state.html |title=Hawaii Bowl - East Carolina vs Boise State Box Score, December 23, 2007 |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=March 17, 2018}}</ref>\n\n====College statistics====\n''Source:<ref>